post_text: Congratulations to Alex Wercinski on being named the 2020 recipient of the Harvard Prize Book. The Harvard Prize Book is an achievement award from the Harvard Alumni Association awarded to an outstanding high school student in the junior class who displays excellence in scholarship and high character, combined with achievements in other fields. The 2020 Harvard Prize Book is Sapiens A Brief History of Humankind by Yuval Noah Harari.

post_text:
Dear parents and students of the Virginia Public Schools

Today the Governor of Minnesota and Commissioner of Education announced that Distance Learning will continue for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Consequently, all schooling will continue to held online. There will be no student instruction on May 1 and May 4. In addition, all high school league activities are officially cancelled for the remainder of the school year. This includes all practices.

Please look for more information to be forthcoming from the building principal and classroom teachers. We want all students to continue working hard on their online assignments and complete all assignments given to them by the teachers.

Thank you.

post_text:
Hello parents of Virginia Public School students,

The Governor of Minnesota and Commissioner of Education have announced (today) that schools will continue to be closed until (at least) April 30th. All distance learning programs for students will begin on Monday, March 30.

We will, however, by order of the Governor, continue providing daycare to families of essential workers. We will also continue providing free breakfast and lunch to students who want one.

We will send out additional information to you by no later than Friday morning of this week (March 27th) on this important topic.

For now, the most important information to know is that Virginia Public Schools, by order of the Governor, will not reopen on Monday, March 30.

We will send out additional information to you by no later than Friday morning of this week (March 27th) on this important topic.

For now, the most important information to know is that Virginia Public Schools, by order of the Governor, will not reopen on Monday, March 30.

post_text:
WEB (7th Grade mentorship program) recognized these 7th graders for doing something great during the past week. Teachers who saw acts of kindness, hard work, and thoughtfulness filled out a WEB Applause Form. After recognizing each student individually, a winner was drawn. Abby Lindberg won a gift card to the VHS Urban Edge and a new Rock Ridge High School T-Shirt.

Each 7th grade student was challenged to do one good thing each day. If every 7th grader did one good thing a day, that would equal 7,280 good things by the end of the school year. That’s a lot of good.

#creatingpositiveculture

post_text: The current construction plans call for construction on the District’s property that is being leased by ERATS, including in the existing parking lots. But, construction is not currently planned on the site of the actual building where ERATS is leasing space due to the unsettled nature of their continued occupancy. This plan could change and construction could take place on the site of the existing building once we settle this issue. Because of how close the construction will be to the existing building, ERATS threatened to sue the District to stop construction if they remain on the site.
text: The current construction plans call for construction on the District’s property that is being leased by ERATS, including in the existing parking lots. But, construction is not currently planned on the site of the actual building where ERATS is leasing space due to the unsettled nature of their continued occupancy. This plan could change and construction could take place on the site of the existing building once we settle this issue. Because of how close the construction will be to the existing building, ERATS threatened to sue the District to stop construction if they remain on the site.

post_text: It was our understanding in conversations with ERATS that they were seeking at least a half million dollars. But this is an extravagant sum of money to simply end a lease. Especially since the State of Minnesota pays most of their monthly rent payment. And the State of Minnesota would continue paying most of their monthly rent payment, even if they were in a different location. We have offered them $250,000 and they have never counter-offered. We feel they have received a more than reasonable settlement offer for ending their lease.
text: It was our understanding in conversations with ERATS that they were seeking at least a half million dollars. But this is an extravagant sum of money to simply end a lease. Especially since the State of Minnesota pays most of their monthly rent payment. And the State of Minnesota would continue paying most of their monthly rent payment, even if they were in a different location. We have offered them $250,000 and they have never counter-offered. We feel they have received a more than reasonable settlement offer for ending their lease.

post_text: The District intends to continue to work directly with ERATS to pursue an amicable arrangement that gives them a new home and appropriate compensation without the need for a court hearing. At the end of the day, the goal is to ensure that students in the Virginia District, Eveleth-Gilbert District, and ERATS school receive an excellent education. If negotiations are unsuccessful, the next major step in the eminent domain process is to petition the court to authorize acquisition of the property through eminent domain and to set a court date for a hearing on the petition. The District hopes to set a court date for this Spring or Summer to ensure it can stay on track with construction timelines. The Virginia District still believes the best way to achieve that goal is through resolution of the matter short of litigation.

The District hopes to set a court date for this Spring or Summer to ensure it can stay on track with construction timelines. The Virginia District still believes the best way to achieve that goal is through resolution of the matter short of litigation.

Eleventh grader Erykah will be awarded the Donaldson STEM Award from the Science Museum of Minnesota. This award recognizes Minnesota high-school students who have demonstrated exceptional achievement in or a passion for a STEM discipline. This award is given to only four students in the state of Minnesota each year. The award ceremony will take place on January 25th, 2020 in St. Paul at the Science Museum of Minnesota during the Latinx Americans in Science Science Fusion Event. Students who earn this award are selected based on their involvement with STEM activities, leadership, and community engagement.
Congratulations Erykah!

Hello staff, students, and parents,

I want to let you know about an incident that occurred this morning. A Virginia High School student made a poor decision in sending an inappropriate text message to another Virginia student. In the text, the student making the inappropriate remarks made a vague statement warning a student to stay away from school. The incident was immediately addressed and is continuing to be investigated by the high school administration team and the Virginia Police Department. The investigation is ongoing and the incident has been resolved. There is no ongoing safety issue for students or staff.

We take student safety seriously at Virginia Public Schools and wanted to give you accurate information as to what actually happened. A voice alert was also sent to all families enrolled at Virginia Public Schools.

If you have any questions, you can call the high school office at (218) 749-5437.

Dr. Noel Schmidt

post_text: 55 of Virginia’s Industrial Technology students from Mr. Foster’s, Mr. Eichholz’s, and Mr. Malone’s class took part in the 218 Trades Expo. Students learned about post secondary technical education options, and learned about how to enter directly into the workforce by joining a union. Several unions were in attendance and created opportunities for hands-on exploration, these unions were the Bricklayers, Electrician, Carpenters, Plumber/Pipefitters, Iron Workers, Labors, and Millwrights Unions. This was a great opportunity for students, Thank You to 218 Trades! To get more information on skilled trades in the 218 area go to: https://www.218trades.com

VMPS Bands is at Virginia High School.
November 2, 2019 at 1:36 PM · Virginia, MN ·

High school student musicians in band, choir, and orchestra had the opportunity to participate in our annual Rock-a-Thon fundraiser last night. Students gathered pledges for each hour they rocked in their rocking chair from 6pm - 6am. It rocked! Thank you to all who pledged or donated to our student musicians as they fundraise for future music trips!

#vmpsbands #marchingband #band #stretch #streetmarching #marchingblues #everyonecounts #everyonematters #createtheculture #inspiregreatness Virginia High School Choirs

post_text: Today Mr. Foster showed his students how to laser engrave pumpkins. We experimented with using the rotary fixture to laser engrave all the way around the pumpkin. We also attempted to laser engrave some of the students faces into the pumpkins using 1 touch photo, but they didn’t turn out that good.

post_text:
Yesterday the Medical Careers class took a field trip to the Virginia Fire Department to explore the station and learn about the EMS, Fire, and rescue services provided out of the fire station. A huge thanks to the Virginia EMS and Fire for letting us visit today and sharing your knowledge with us!
Earlier this month the class took a trip to the Bauman Family Funeral home to visit with Bill Bauman. Mr. Bauman shared with us the world of mortuary science and what it is like to work in his profession. Thank you so much for shedding light on a little known profession!

post_text: Industrial Technology students from Mr. Fosters, Mr. Eichholz, and Mr. Malones classes took part in a 218 Trades presentation. Nina and Maria who are career counselors from the MN Workforce Center lead today’s presentation. The focus of this presentation was to learn about technical careers, apprenticeships, 2-year degrees, unions, and funding options. In small groups students explored different careers using the 218 Trades website and then shared what they discovered with the rest of the class. To get more information on skilled trades in the 218 area go to: https://www.218trades.com

post_text:
Today Arynn Lorentz, current Iron Range Engineering Senior and 2016 VHS graduate, spoke to chemistry, environmental science, and physics classes about careers in engineering and the Iron Range Engineering Program. During the presentation students used critical thinking and problem solving skills during a game of Mockups where they were given a user (client), a need, and a constraint. Students presented their solutions to their classmates at the end of the game. This game is similar to the design process engineers use to solve problems.

Iron Range Engineering is a 4 year engineering program located in Virginia, MN. IRE was named number 5th in the world in a study conducted by MIT called, “The global state of the art in engineering education.”
